<head>
   <title> Try It Yourself </title>
   <style type="text/css">
      table {
         border-collapse: collapse;
         font-family: sans-serif;
      }
      table, th, td {
         border: 1px solid black;
         padding: 5px;
      }
      .table1 tbody > tr:nth-child(2), .table1 tr:nth-child(5) {
         background: #173459;
         color: #f8f9f9;
      }
      .table2 tbody > tr:nth-child(odd) {
         background: #173459;
         color: #f8f9f9;
      }
      .table3 tbody > tr:nth-child(even) {
         background: #173459;
         color: #f8f9f9;
      }
   </style>
</head>
<body>
   <p> The <b>:nth-child</b> CSS pseudo-class matches elements based on their position in a group of siblings. </p>
   <p> Valid Values: </p>
   <ul>
      <li> <b>&lt;number&gt;</b> </li>
      <li> <b>odd</b>: represents elements whose numeric position in a series of siblings is odd e.g. 1, 3, 5 </li>
      <li> <b>even</b>: represents elements whose numeric position in a series of siblings is even e.g. 2, 4, 6 </li>
   </ul>
   
   <h3> Example #1: </h3>
   <p> In this example, only the <b>2nd</b> and <b>5th</b> rows are selected from the table's body. </p>
   <table class="table1">
      <thead>
         <tr>
            <th> First Name </th>
            <th> Last Name </th>
            <th> Gender </th>
         </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
         <tr>
            <td> Rickert </td>
            <td> Gonnet </td>
            <td> Male </td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
            <td> Jesica </td>
            <td> Fortie </td>
            <td> Female </td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
            <td> Lindon </td>
            <td> Scarse </td>
            <td> Male </td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
            <td> Ezechiela </td>
            <td> Mortlock </td>
            <td> Female </td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
            <td> Abran </td>
            <td> Coatts </td>
            <td> Male </td>
         </tr>
         <tr>
            <td> Dewskie </td>
            <td> Suda </td>
            <td> Male </td>
         </tr>
      </tbody>
   </table>
   
   <h3> Example #2: </h3>
